    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`vim.fs.ext()` currently only returns the last file extension (similar to `fnamemodify(file, ':e')`). Sometimes it it useful to get all extensions, mostly in case of tar archive files: e.g. `.tar.gz`, `.tar.bz2`, and `.tar.xz`. See https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/38744/changes#r3037084208 for example.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nMultiple approaches possible, and I would like to hear which one seems best:\n\n## Signature\n1. `vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true })` (default: `false`): simple, either all or just the one.\n2. `vim.fs.ext(file, { max = 2 })` (default: `1`): Might be easier to use if you want to check exactly X possible extensions. Note that this might return less than the given number.\n\n## Return value\n1. A string: `tar.gz`: simple but would still need to require manual string parsing if you're not doing a simple \"equals\" check.\n2. An array of extensions: `{ 'tar', 'gz' }`: Feels more \"right\" and easier to check e.g. just the first (`tar`). No manual string parsing needed. Harder to use if you want to check if it equals certain extensions as Lua or not comparable with `==`.\n\n\n## Comparison of return value\n\n```lua\nlocal file = 'test.tar.gz'\n\n-- string return, full equal\nif vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true }) == 'tar.gz' then\n  print('tar.gz whooo')\nend\n\n-- string return, partial equal\nif vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true }):gsub('%..*', '') == 'tar' then\n  print('tar whooo')\nend\n\n-- array return, full equal\nif vim.deep_equal(vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true }), { 'tar', 'gz' }) then\n  print('tar.gz whooo')\nend\n-- or\nif table.concat(vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true }), '.') == 'tar.gz' then\n  print('tar.gz whooo')\nend\n\n-- array return, partial equal\nif vim.fs.ext(file, { all = true })[1] == 'tar' then\n  print('tar whooo')\nend\n```\n\ncc @justinmk ",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
